\section*{POPs: Mechanism of action.}
- Suppress ovulation- Mental function.
- Thicken cervical mucus (preventing sperm penetration).

\section*{POPs: Advantages.}
- Highly effective (97\%).
- Safe (have no known health risks).
- Return to fertility is immediate after discontinuation.
- Pelvic examination is not required to initiate use.
- Can be given to women to start any time provided that pregnancy is ruled out.
- Does not affect milk production or breastfeeding.
- Enhance contraceptive effect of breastfeeding.
- Does not increase blood clotting.

\section*{POPs: Limitations.}
- Does not protect against STIs including HIV/AIDS and hepatitis B.
- They provide slightly lower level of contraception than COCs.
- Require strict daily taking preferably the same time every day.
- May lower effectiveness when certain drugs are taken concurrently e.g. certain antituberculosis drugs, anti-retroviral and anti-epileptic drugs.

\section*{POPs: Side effects.}
- Irregular spotting or bleeding, frequent or infrequent bleeding or prolonged bleeding.
- Amenorrhea (absence of menses).
- Headaches.
- Dizziness.
- Nausea.
- Mood changes.
- Breast tenderness which is less common than COCs.

\section*{Recommended Category for POPs.}

\section*{Women:}
- Of any parity including women who have never given birth (nulliparous).
- Immediate postpartum if not breastfeeding.
- Breastfeeding mother four weeks postpartum.
- Any age who are cigarette smokers.
- Who cannot use COCs due to estrogen related contraindications
- Post abortion clients.
- With hypertension, sickle cell disease, benign breast disease, viral hepatitis, acute or chronic or compensated (mild) cirrhosis.
- Obese women and girls with BMI greater than $30 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m} 2$.

\section*{POPs: When to initiate.}
- Anytime you can be reasonably sure the client is not pregnant.
- If it has been more than 5 days since menstrual bleeding started, she will need to abstain from sex who use another method for the next 2 days.
- Postpartum:
- After 6 months if using lactational amenorrhea method (LAM).
- After 4 weeks if breastfeeding but not using LAM.

O After 4 weeks if not breastfeeding.
- Post abortion within 5 days and if later than this use back up method for the next 2 days.

\section*{POPs: Client instructions.}
- Take 1 pill at the same time each day.
- Take first pill on first day of your menstrual period.
- If you start POPs after the first day of your menstrual period, but before the seventh day, use a backup method for the next 48 hours.
- Take all pills in pack.
- Start a new pack on the day after you take last pill.
- If you vomit within 30 minutes of taking pill, take another pill or use a backup method if you have sex during the next 48 hours.
- If you take a pill more than 3 hours late, take it as soon as you remember.
- Use a backup method if you have sex during the next 48 hours.
- If you forget to take 1 or more pills, you should take the next pill when you remember.
- Use a backup method if you have sex during the next 48 hours.
- If you miss 2 or more menstrual periods, you should go to the clinic to check to see if you are pregnant.
- Do not stop taking pills unless you know you are pregnant.

\section*{Problems that may require switching of method.}
1. Unexplained Vaginal Bleeding.
- Condition needs evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment as appropriate.
- Client can continue using POPs while her condition is being evaluated.
- If the bleeding is caused by an STI or a PID, she can continue using POPs during treatment.
2. Starting Treatment with Anticonvulsants, Rifampicin, Rifabutin or Ritonavir.
- If medication require long term treatment client may choose an alternative method.
- If treatment is short term client may use a backup method in addition to POPs.
3. Migraine (Severe) headache.
- Migraine headaches without aura (disturbance), client can continue to use POPs if she wishes.
- Migraine headaches with aura, a client should stop taking POPs, and provider helps her choose a method without hormones.

\section*{4. Certain serious health conditions.}
- These might include liver disease, ischemic heart disease or stroke, breast cancer, etc.
- If the condition becomes worse after the client starts using POPs, she should stop immediately.
- Help her choose another method.

\section*{5. Suspected pregnancy.}
- Assess client for pregnancy and if pregnancy is confirmed including ectopic pregnancy instruct her to stop taking POPs.

\section*{EMERGENCY CONTRACEPTION.}

What it is?.
- Contraceptive methods used to prevent pregnancy after unprotected sex

Also known as:
- Morning-After Pills
- Post-coital Contraception

Effective if taken within $\mathbf{1 2 0}$ hrs
- ECPs seem to prevent between75-95\% percent of pregnancies that would otherwise have occurred.
- The average chance of pregnancy resulting from one act of unprotected intercourse in the second or third week of the menstrual cycle is estimated at $8 \%$.
- After emergency oral contraception it is $1.2 \%$.
- ECPs prevent pregnancy through:
1. Preventing or delaying ovulation
2. Inhibiting or slowing down transportation of egg and sperm through the fallopian tubes which prevents fertilization and implantation.

\section*{Emergency Contraception:}

\section*{Types.}
- Combined Oral Contraceptives (COCs):
- Low-dose ( $30-35 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ Ethinly Estradiol and $150 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ Levonogestrel) e.g. Microgynon- 4 tablets immediately, repeat dose after 12 hrs .
- High-dose ( $50 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ Ethinly Estradiol and $250 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ LNG) e.g. Eugynon- 2 tablets immediately, repeat dose after 12 hrs .
- Progestin-Only Pills (POPs):
- Levonogestrel (preferred e.g. Postinor 2-1 tablet, repeat after 12hrs or 2 tablets as single dose).
- Regular POPs (Microlut-20 tablets and repeat after 12 hrs ).
- Intra- Uterine- Device (IUDs): e.g TCu 380A, Multi-load 375, Nova T, Mirena.

\section*{Emergency Contraception:}

\section*{Advantages.}
- Safe, effective and easy to use.
- No medical examination or pregnancy tests are necessary or required.
- It can be used at any time during the menstrual cycle.
- ECPs are available in government, private, and NGO health facilities; and over the counter at pharmacies.

\section*{Emergency Contraception:}

\section*{Limitations.}
- ECPs are only effective if used within 120 hours of unprotected intercourse.
- They are not to be used as a regular method.
- ECPs do not protect against STls, HIV, or AIDS.
- They can cause nausea (more common for the COC regimen).

\section*{Medical Eligibility Criteria (MEC) category 1.}

EC should be used under the following conditions:
- Sex took place without contraception, and the woman wants to avoid pregnancy.
- A woman has run out of oral contraceptives, has missed two or more POPs, or is more than four weeks late for her Depo injection, and has had unprotected intercourse.
- A woman has had coerced sexual intercourse, such as rape.
- A condom has broken.
- An IUCD has come out of place.

\section*{MEC category 2.}
- Frequently repeated EC use may be harmful for women with conditions classified as "Who should not use" for hormonal methods.
- ECPs should not be given to women who are known to be pregnant, but if ECPs are accidentally used by a woman who is pregnant, there is no known harm to the woman, the course of her pregnancy, or the baby.

\section*{Post-coital IUD insertion.}
- Mechanisms of action:
- May prevent fertilization by interfering with sperm transport or function
- May prevent implantation by altering tubal or endometrial environment
- Effectiveness
$\mathrm{O}<1 \%$ failure rate.
- Safety.
- No adverse fetal effects (should be removed if pregnancy not prevented)
- Should not be inserted for women at risk for STDs (e.g., HBV, HIV/AIDS).

\section*{IUDs: Instructions for Use as Emergency Contraception.}
- Step 1: Insert IUD within 5 days of unprotected intercourse.
- Step 2: If no menses within 3 weeks, the client should consult the clinic or service provider to check for possible pregnancy.
- Step 3: If pregnancy not prevented, counsel client regarding options.

\section*{INJECTABLE CONTRACEPTIVES.}
- Contain one or two hormones and provide protection from pregnancy for one, two or three months depending on type.
- The progestin only injectable contain synthetic progesterone similar to the natural hormone in a woman's body.

\section*{Types of Injectables:}
- Depot medroxyprogesterone acetate (DMPA or Depo- provera).
- Northisterone enanthate (NET-EN or Noristerat).

\section*{Mechanism of action.}
- Suppression of ovulation.
- Thickening of the cervical mucus.
- Thinning of the endometrium which makes implantation unlikely.

\section*{Injectable progestin:}

\section*{Advantages.}
- Highly effective, reversible.
- No pelvic examination required to initiate use.
- They are long acting.
- Assure clients' confidentiality.
- Do not contain estrogen therefore no cardiac and blood clot effects.
- Decreases sickle cell crisis.
- Protects against endometrial cancer and possibly ovarian cancer.

\section*{Injectable progestin:}

\section*{Disadvantages.}
- Delay in return of fertility after discontinuation.
- Common side effects such as bleeding changes such as spotting, heavy and/or prolonged bleeding or amenorrhea.
- Progestin injectables do not protect against STI/HIV individuals at risk should in addition use condoms.
- Other side effects include nausea, headache, breast tenderness and mood swings.

\section*{MEC for progestin injectables category 1.}

\section*{Women.}
- Who had children or have never given birth (nulliparous women).
- Who want highly effective, long-term protection against pregnancy.
- Who are breastfeeding (after four weeks postpartum).
- Who are not breastfeeding (immediate postpartum).
- With fibroids, endometrial cancer, or benign breast disease.
- Who cannot remember to take the pill every day, post-abortion clients.
- With anaemia, sickle cell disease, and thyroid disease.
- With STIs and PID.
- With family history of DVT and those that have had minor or major surgery without prolonged immobilization.
- With gestational trophoblastic disease.
- With viral hepatitis and those with mild liver cirrhosis and women with obesity (i.e., BMI greater than $30 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m} 2$ ).

\section*{MEC for progestin injectables category 2.}

\section*{Women.}
- Who are younger than 18 or older than 45.
- With decreased bone density, heavy or irregular vaginal bleeding pattern.
- Cervical cancer awaiting treatment.
- With migraine without aura.
- With history of DVT and established on anticoagulant therapy, known thrombogenic mutations or major surgery with prolonged immobilization.
- On immunosuppressive treatment.
- Without severe thrombocytopenia, history of hypertension, adequately controlled BP, or BP between 140/90 and 159/99.
- Women diagnosed of AIDS and under treatment with ARVs.

\section*{Client instructions for progestin injectables.}
- Within five days after the start of the monthly period.
- If more than five days after the start of her period she can commence injectables but will require a backup method for the first seven days post injection.
- If she is switching from an IUD she can start injectables immediately.
- If switching from an hormonal method used correctly no need to wait for the next monthly bleeding she can start immediately.

\section*{In breastfeeding mothers.}
- Delay the first injection to 4 weeks postpartum.
- If her menses has not returned she can start injectables anytime between four weeks and six months.

\section*{If the mother is more than six months.}
- If the menses are not returned he can commence any time after excluding pregnancy.
- A backup method will be required for the first seven days after the injection.
- Mothers with resumed menses can start within the first five days.

\section*{Women not breastfeeding.}
- Less than four weeks post-delivery can start at any time and there is no need for backup.
- If more than four weeks postpartum and the menses have not returned, rule out pregnancy, start injectables and give backup for the first seven days.
- If the menses have returned she can start the injectables immediately.

If client has no menses (not related to childbirth or breastfeeding and not pregnant).
- Commence injectables and issue backup for the first seven days.

\section*{After miscarriage or abortion.}
- If within 7 days of $1^{\text {st }}$ or $2^{\text {nd }}$ trimester miscarriage start immediately.
- No need for backup.
- If more than 7 days after $1^{\text {st }}$ or $2^{\text {nd }}$ trimester miscarriage start injectable and give backup method for the next seven days.

\section*{After taking emergency contraceptive pills.}
- Clients can start injectables on the same day as the Emergency contraceptives.
- If preferred within 7 days of starting her monthly period, this will require a backup method for the first seven days post injection.
- Be weary to look out for signs and symptoms of continued pregnancy.

\section*{How to administer the injection.}
- Aseptic technique with infection protocol to be observed.
- Injection site deep into the, upper arm deltoid muscle or the buttock upper outer portion (gluteal muscle).
- Do not massage the injection site.

\section*{COMBINED PATCHES.}

\section*{What it is?}
- A small thin square of flexible plastic worn on the body.
- It continuously releases progestin and estrogen like the natural hormones in a woman's body directly through the skin into the blood stream.
- It is worn every day and night for three weeks then no patch for the fourth week.
- Its during the fourth week the woman will get her menses.

\section*{Types.}
- Ortho Evra.
- Evra.

\section*{Mechanism of action:}
- Primarily inhibits ovulation.

\section*{Effectiveness:}
- 97\%

\section*{Medical eligibility criteria (MEC):}
- Refer to COCs.

\section*{Side effects and management:}
- Specific patches have skin irritation at site of application.
- Flu symptoms.
- There are other effects similar to COCs and are managed as indicated.

\section*{Client instructions for combined patch.}
- Client can apply the patch to the upper outer arm, back, stomach or buttocks whenever its clean and dry.
- Do not apply on the breasts.
- Pressure for 10 sec to be applied on the adhesive side of the patch against the skin weekly and must be changed on the same day (patch change day) for three consecutive weeks.
- After the patch free week a new patch must be applied.
- Never go without wearing a patch for more than seven days.

\section*{Late removal or replacement.}
- Apply a new patch as soon as possible.
- Record this day of the week as the new patch change day.
- Use a backup method for the next seven days of patch use.
- If a new patch was applied three or more days late and the client had unprotected sex in the past five days gives ECPs.
- If the client forgot to change the patch by one or two days in the middle of the patch cycle (during week 2 or 3) apply a new patch as soon as you remember.
- No need for backup method.
- If late by more than 2 days, stop the current cycle and start a new four week cycle immediately.
- Record this day as the new patch change day and use a backup method for seven days.
- If client forgot to remove at the end of four weeks, remove the patch and start the next cycle on the usual patch change day.
- No need for backup.

\section*{COMBINED VAGINAL RING.}

\section*{Mechanism of action:}
- Primarily works by inhibiting ovulation.

\section*{Effectiveness:}
- 97\%.

\section*{Side effects and management:}
- Specific to the rings are irritation, vaginitis and vaginal discharges.
- The rest are similar to COCs and are managed appropriately.

\section*{Client instructions:}

How to insert the ring.
- The client assumes either a standing position with one leg up, squatting or lithotomy position.
- She compresses opposite side of the ring together and gently pushes the folded ring entirely deeply inside the vagina.
- The muscles of the vagina naturally keep the ring in place.
- The ring must be kept in place day and night for three weeks.
- At the end of the third week the client removes the ring and disposes it.
- To remove the ring the client should hook her index finger inside it or squeeze the ring between her index and middle fingers and pulls it out.
- She will probably have her menses during this week.
- Is she forgets and extends the ring for more than four weeks, no special attention is required.
- The ring can be removed for sex, cleaning or other reason but should not be left out more than three hours until the fourth week.
- If the ring accidentally slips out, she should rinse it in clean water and immediately reinsert it.
- If the ring is left out for more than three hours in the first and second week.
- It should be returned as soon as possible and a backup method given for the first seven days.
- If the ring is kept out for more than three hours in the third week stop the current cycle and discard the ring.
- Insert a new ring and leave in place for three weeks.
- A backup method must be in place for the next seven days.
- Alternatively if the rings had been used continuously and correctly for the past seven days, leave the ring out and make the next seven days the week with no ring.
- After these seven days insert a new ring and keep in place for the next three weeks.
- A backup method for the first seven days with the new ring to be given.
- If client waited more than seven days before inserting a new ring or kept the ring in more than four weeks insert a new ring as soon as possible and use a backup method for the first seven days of ring use.
- Also if a new ring was inserted three or more days late and client had unprotected sex in the past five days consider use of ECP.

\section*{IMPLANTS.}

\section*{What are they?}
- Small rods that are inserted under the skin of a woman's upper arm to release the hormone progestin slowly and prevent pregnancy.
- They do not contain estrogen.
- They are free of the side effects associated with the hormone.

\section*{Implants: Effectiveness.}
- Over 99\% effective.
- Effective contraceptive within <24 hours.

\section*{Implants: Advantages.}
- Highly effective and safe.
- Contraception is immediate if inserted within the first seven days of menstrual cycle, or within the first five days for Implanon.
- There is no delay in return to fertility.
- They offer continuous long-term protection against pregnancy.

\section*{Implants: Non-contraceptive benefits.}
- Do not affect breastfeeding.
- Reduce menstrual flow.
- Help prevent ectopic pregnancy (but do not eliminate the risk altogether).
- Protect against iron-deficiency anaemia.
- Help protect from symptomatic PID.

\section*{Implants: Limitations and side effects.}
- Contraceptive implants must be inserted and removed by trained providers.
- This requires a minor surgical procedure with appropriate infection prevention practices.
- Common side effects of using implants include menstrual changes, such as irregular light spotting or bleeding, prolonged bleeding, infrequent bleeding, and amenorrhea.
- Non-menstrual side effects include headache, dizziness, nausea, breast tenderness, mood changes, weight change, and mild abdominal pain.
- Do not protect against STIs, including hepatitis B and HIV.
- Individuals at risk should use condoms in addition to the implants.

\section*{Medical Eligibility Criteria (MEC) Category 1 for implants.}
- Women of reproductive age, from menarche to menopause, with or without children.
- Breastfeeding mothers after four weeks postpartum, or immediate postpartum if not breastfeeding.
- Women who prefer not to use or have contraindications to contraceptives that contain oestrogen or have developed oestrogen-related complications while taking COCs.
- Women with STIs and PID.
- Women with HIV and AIDS, unless they are on ARV therapy.
- Women with adequately controlled or moderate hypertension (BP is less than $160 / 100$ ) and those with history of hypertension during pregnancy.
- Women who have had major and minor surgery without prolonged immobilization.
- Women who take broad-spectrum antibiotics, antifungal or antiparasitics.
- Women with any of the following conditions:
- Valvular heart disease.
- Sickle cell disease.
- Non-migrainous headache or depressive disorders.
- Endometriosis, severe dysmenorrhoea, benign ovarian tumours, fibroids.
- Benign breast tumours, endometrial and ovarian cancer.
- Goitre.
- Viral hepatitis or mild liver cirrhosis.

\section*{MEC category 2 for implants. \\ Women with:}
- Irregular, prolonged or heavy bleeding patterns.
- Diabetes without or with vascular complications.
- Woman with multiple risk factors for cardiovascular disease (e.g., more than 35 years of age, cigarette smoking, diabetes, and hypertension).
- Women with ischemic heart disease or stroke (can initiate implants, but will have to discontinue if they develop these conditions while using the method).
- History of hypertension where BP cannot be measured.
- Severe hypertension (BP of 160/100 or higher).
- Migraine with or without aura.
- History of DVT and established on anticoagulant therapy, major surgery with prolonged immobilization.
- Gall bladder disease, symptomatic or asymptomatic.
- Diagnosed cervical cancer (risk of sterility).
- Undiagnosed breast mass (prompt evaluation needed, breast cancer is category 4).
- Women with severe thrombocytopenia or on immunosuppressive treatment.
- Receiving treatment with certain ARVs, anticonvulsants, and anti-TB drugs that may reduce blood concentration of contraceptive hormones to some degree.

\section*{When to insert implants.}
- Days 1 to 7 of the menstrual cycle (day 5 for Implanon).
- Anytime you are reasonably sure the client is not pregnant.
- Postpartum:
- After 6 months if using lactational amenorrhea method (LAM).
- After 4 weeks if breastfeeding but not using LAM.

O Within 4 weeks if not breastfeeding.
- Post abortion (immediately or within the first 7 days).

\section*{Implants: Drug Interactions.}
- Most interactions relate to increased liver metabolism of levonorgestrel:
- Rifampin (tuberculosis).
- Anti-epilepsy (seizures):
- Griseofulvin (long-term use only).

\section*{Implants: Client Instructions.}
- Keep incision area dry for 4 to 5 days.
- Remove gauze bandage after one or two days but leave adhesive plaster in place for additional 5 days.
- Bruising, swelling and tenderness at insertion site are common.
- Routine work can be done immediately.
- Avoid bumping the area, carrying heavy loads or applying unusual pressure to incision site.
- After healing, area can be touched and washed with normal pressure.
- Return to clinic if rods come out or soreness develops after removing adhesive tape
- Return to clinic if she experiences pain, heat, pus or redness at incision site.

\section*{Implants: Warning Signs}
- Return to clinic if any of the following occur:
- Severe lower abdominal pain.
- Delayed menstrual period after several months of regular cycles (may be sign of pregnancy).
- Heavy bleeding.
- Pus or bleeding at insertion site.
- Infection at insertion site.
- Expulsion.
- Migraine headaches.

