\section*{4). Poems.}
- A poem is an art form in which human language is used for its aesthetic qualities in addition to, or instead of its notional and semantic content.
- It consists largely of oral or literary works in which language is used in a manner that is felt by its user and audience to differ from ordinary prose.
- There are certain ingredients that are important when composing a poem;
a) Message.

What are you trying to say?. The message of your poem is the most important part.
It could be something as simple, or it could be something more complex, like a relationship.
Whatever it is, your message should be clear to the audience.

\section*{b). Form/Structure.}

Will the length/shape of each stanza enhance the poem in any way? Think carefully about how the poem is formulated. A poem particularly a concrete one can be a piece of art and should be attractive and friendly to listeners.

\section*{c). Point of View.}

Whose perspective are you writing your poem from? The perspective you write your poem from can dramatically change its meaning and impact on the audience.

\section*{d). Voice/Tone.}

Voice is important in everything that you write or speak, and poem is no different.
The important thing is to make sure that the tone you've chosen fits the poem and the message you want to get across. Don't write or say something in a serious way if you're trying to be funny and don't go overboard with the jokes if you're trying to be serious.

\section*{e). Rhythm.}

You may find that your poem naturally fits into or suits a particular rhythm. Perhaps the most vital element of sound in poetry is rhythm. Often, the rhythm of each line is arranged in a particular manner.

\section*{f). Grammar.}

Grammar is incredibly important in a poem. Its absence can tell you as much as its usage. This allows you to manipulate it to your advantage and even alter the meaning of your poem.

